Hi Ariane,

Hmm, that's strange - the order of variables shouldn't make a difference. I would expect the Matlab implementation of linear regression to be reliable, so we can probably rule out a software glitch. Just to be sure though, you may try the linear regression example here: https://uk.mathworks.com/help/stats/linear-regression-workflow.html - check whether changing the order of variables in 'modelspec' changes the R-squared value. Assuming it doesn't, I'm not sure what could be going on...

With respect to the difference between rabi/kharif, I think your explanation is a good one - with very few exceptions it's impossible to grow crops in the rabi season without irrigation, so the impact of drought will be much reduced and hence we do not see the same impact of drought.

I can't remember how you compute the NDVI anomaly? You could try calculating as the difference between the theoretical maximum NDVI value (i.e. 1) and the maximum seasonal value. This might enable the model to pick up differences between villages that aren't just related to irrigation. Try this - see what happens.

We could meet tomorrow late afternoon - say 4pm?

